The importance of developing our own systems are as follows:
1. Obviously there is the complete and utter optimisation of development efficiency, reliability, speed and control but further to that we also optimise and capture as much value as possible because truth be told that the REAL value of each and every developer isn't just the code that they produce but it's the bi-products of that, the prior thinking, the idea generation and problem solving that they do in the process of trying to acheive their objective.
Capturing, enabling, gathering and ultimately using all of this information to further enable and optimise our own development is critical to the ongoing expeditious development of this system.
2. Ensuring complete code control and management in as simple way as possible, AKA with the tightest skilset requirements possible means that not only can we streamline our productivity improvement internally but also our hiring can be as broad as possible to just highly intelligent humans AND all our educational material can also be streamlined so it has huge business benefits other than just the development of code
3. ESPECIALLY AND PROBABLY MOST NOTABLY As this business is both a consultancy and a technology company getting lost in anything "deeper" than straight up PHP code, AJAX, HTML, SQL and a dash of javascript (where there are no other options), is not only too much of a stretch in terms of mental focus in the initial growth phases of the business but it also causes waste and confusion further than is required. NOTHING, NOTHING we are doing is so unique that it requuires some custom CMS or framework or other rubbish frankly, and any move to do so would only curtail our business by increasing the training costs, decreasing our potential talent pool and what for? it's frankly insane.
4. Ultimately building a network of developers is essentially what is going on here, much the same as the pilots will turn into a network of sorts and while there will be some cross pollination/connection both deserve/and require their own networks without doubt. Most cross poliation will be via requests and responses to those requests really but they both operate on largely different systems


It is important to note that for the forseeable future expanding/going deeper into server maintenance etc etc is not going to be done as we live on siteground and when / if we outgrow that we simply move to Oracle.


